Now, I know it's Thanksgiving weekend, but we are systematically walking through the Book of Acts together and so we're at this really brilliant pivotal point in the Book of Acts.

00:44.022 --> 00:49.411
That actually is really exciting and would produce a lot of Thanksgiving and also is a little heavy.

00:49.732 --> 00:52.576
So, I hope you'll join me as we get going.

00:52.676 --> 00:56.242
Jesus, long before he was set up and

00:56.354 --> 01:04.927
murdered and crucified and rose from the dead, warned his followers that things would be amazing and things would also be difficult.

01:05.788 --> 01:15.803
This is what he said in Luke 12, when you're brought before the synagogue or rulers or authorities, don't worry about how you'll defend yourself or what you even say.

01:15.843 --> 01:20.210
For the Holy Spirit will teach you at that time what you should say.

01:21.411 --> 01:25.778
Well, Jesus doesn't lie and that's exactly what happened.

01:26.306 --> 01:31.556
Now it didn't begin with a fight or a dispute or violence or a vote or some mob moment.

01:32.097 --> 01:37.687
It happened actually in a really amazing place that was actually full of Thanksgiving.

01:38.548 --> 01:42.315
It happens in an encounter marked by mercy and healing compassion.

01:42.395 --> 01:44.299
So let's begin where we did last week.

01:44.359 --> 01:46.763
We're in the city of Jerusalem.

01:47.605 --> 01:49.388
Now, a new character comes on the scene.

01:49.609 --> 01:50.450
There's a beggar.

01:50.530 --> 01:53.995
sitting outside of the very world-famous Jewish temple.

01:54.416 --> 02:00.986
Now, his experience, like many of others, millions before millions after, is basically not that great.

02:01.687 --> 02:03.450
Nothing but the grind of nothingness.

02:03.530 --> 02:08.838
Day after day, humiliation and rejection, and I guarantee most people didn't look him in the eyes.

02:09.059 --> 02:10.741
Many did not acknowledge his presence.

02:11.222 --> 02:13.746
I guarantee almost no one thought he was valuable.

02:14.018 --> 02:17.984
Now, he's at God's temple and he begged there as we're going to find out for years.

02:18.584 --> 02:23.551
He had seen, well, millions of people come and go to worship the true living God and meet him.

02:24.172 --> 02:30.762
So, it's another normal day for him and two more religious people walk by him and he basically says, money?

02:31.623 --> 02:32.444
Can I have some money?

02:33.165 --> 02:41.076
Now, the strangers, unlike so many others, don't either A ignore him or B, give him some money because it's the right religious thing to do.

02:41.136 --> 02:42.418
They stop.

02:43.234 --> 02:46.938
They look down and they look into his face.

02:46.978 --> 02:53.784
It's almost like I imagine Peter and John looking into the deep, empty, hollow dead before dead eyes.

02:54.425 --> 02:56.347
And suddenly Peter speaks.

02:56.367 --> 02:59.189
He says, oh, silver and gold, I do not have.

02:59.610 --> 03:02.212
But what I do have, I give to you.

03:03.113 --> 03:06.957
In the name of Jesus, the Messiah of Nazareth, walk.

03:07.657 --> 03:09.699
Taking him by the hand, the right hand, he helped him up.

03:10.020 --> 03:12.402
And instantly the man's feet and ankles became

03:12.674 --> 03:13.235
strong.

03:13.275 --> 03:14.216
He jumped to his feet.

03:14.316 --> 03:15.297
He began to walk.

03:15.617 --> 03:19.522
Then he went into the temple courts, walking and jumping and praising God.

03:19.562 --> 03:29.132
And when all the people saw him walking and praising God, they recognized him as the guy who used to sit begging at the temple gate called beautiful.

03:29.833 --> 03:32.296
And they were filled with wonder and amazement at what happened to him.

03:32.976 --> 03:35.499
So can you first of all hear the guys' thoughts?

03:36.400 --> 03:37.321
I thought I would never walk.

03:38.102 --> 03:39.283
I thought I would never have dignity.

03:40.084 --> 03:41.586
I didn't think people really cared.

03:42.018 --> 03:43.600
I wasn't even sure God cared.

03:44.281 --> 03:46.624
I sit at God's house all the time, but does he hear me?

03:46.664 --> 03:53.193
See, my identity is based on beggar, crippled, dirty, lazy, unclean, worthless, garbage, untouchable.

03:53.613 --> 03:55.556
That is his existence in a few words.

03:56.477 --> 04:00.081
And what's even more difficult is this, he's been crippled from birth.

04:00.883 --> 04:09.714
So in the Jewish understanding, if you're born with a deformity or if you're born with a disability, that is evidence that your parents send

04:09.954 --> 04:12.356
or actually if it happens to you later, you sinned.

04:12.837 --> 04:20.965
In other words, the view was God had given you a physical disability as a sign of his displeasure and judgment on you and your family.

04:21.325 --> 04:26.370
So all these religious people walking by him would have gone, God's judgment, God's judgment, God's judgment, God's judgment.

04:27.231 --> 04:31.595
And suddenly this guy is like full of life.

04:32.356 --> 04:35.659
He literally in a few seconds moves from darkness to light.

04:36.040 --> 04:38.322
He's spiritually, physically, emotionally,

04:38.402 --> 04:46.574
transformed, he's got dignity, he's got love, desperation is met in and through the name of Jesus from Nazareth.

04:47.195 --> 04:55.146
And I can imagine him saying, finally, what I have begged in front of my whole life, the gate called beautiful, that is now me.

04:55.166 --> 04:57.510
I can claim that gate is my own.

04:57.570 --> 04:58.511
I am beautiful.

04:59.052 --> 05:00.154
And I'm sure it began to dance.

05:00.935 --> 05:04.039
Like, if there was ever a Thanksgiving passage, it's this.

05:04.901 --> 05:05.842
And I guarantee

05:06.050 --> 05:10.314
He's literally running and yelling, I can walk, I can walk, and I can walk.

05:10.614 --> 05:15.399
He wasn't trying to curate some content to guard his reputation.

05:15.459 --> 05:18.622
He didn't give a rip what people thought about as his reputation.

05:18.702 --> 05:21.805
This was just like epic.

05:21.825 --> 05:23.187
Now remember this, this is important.

05:23.207 --> 05:28.912
Whether you're a seeker, skeptic, brand new Christian long term, miracles are always door opening events.

05:29.653 --> 05:31.294
So actually the good news gets to be shared.

05:31.695 --> 05:35.058
The healer is more important even than the healing.

05:35.874 --> 05:57.238
So Peter turns to the crowd in shock, in amazement, in the middle of the temple, and he begins to preach, and his message is very similar to what we heard last week in the very first Christian sermon, full of bad news and full of good news, and he paints the picture, and he points to the man, and then he points to the crowd, and this is what he says in verse 15.

05:58.079 --> 06:02.084
You all, y'all, you killed the author of life.

06:02.624 --> 06:04.146
Wow, how not to start a sermon?

06:04.546 --> 06:06.729
But God raised Jesus from the dead.

06:06.989 --> 06:07.910
We're witnesses of this.

06:08.030 --> 06:18.704
By faith in the name of Jesus, this man whom you see and know is made strong, it is in Jesus' name and faith that comes through him that has completely healed him as you could all now see.

06:19.064 --> 06:31.920
Now, my fellow Jews, my fellow Israelites, I know that you acted in ignorance as did your leaders, but this is how God fulfilled what he foretold through the prophets, saying the Messiah would suffer.

06:32.681 --> 06:33.362
Repent.

06:34.050 --> 06:46.263
Turn to God that your sins might be wiped out and that times of refreshing may come from God and that he may send the Messiah who has been appointed for you, even Jesus.

06:46.744 --> 06:54.432
Now, like I shared last week, Jesus is coming and Jesus' death was God's plan all along to save us.

06:55.353 --> 07:01.900
Yes, the Romans and some Jewish leaders and Peter says, and a lot of you, God Jesus killed.

07:03.421 --> 07:03.922
Yes.

07:04.322 --> 07:08.507
Some people said Jesus was guilty of treason because he claimed to be the king of the Jews.

07:09.388 --> 07:17.258
Many religious Jewish leaders and even many in that crowd accused Jesus of blasphemy because he claimed he could forgive sins and he was equal to the father.

07:18.119 --> 07:26.689
And Peter basically says once again, you thought you were in charge and they thought they were in charge, but this was God's plan all along and we all got it played.

07:27.009 --> 07:29.492
This is how we get out of the mess we're in.

07:29.532 --> 07:32.155
We need to repent, we need to turn back to God.

07:32.756 --> 07:34.258
But let me slow down.

07:34.914 --> 07:36.195
and point this out again.

07:36.235 --> 07:42.262
See, this is not spiritual anxiety.

07:42.382 --> 07:45.706
Something's wrong, and I know something's wrong, but I'm not sure what it is.

07:46.347 --> 07:47.408
Peter says, no, no, no.

07:48.169 --> 07:50.672
Repentance means, I am guilty.

07:51.472 --> 07:53.154
I know I have done a wrong thing.

07:53.194 --> 07:55.317
It is personal responsibility.

07:55.717 --> 08:02.485
And Peter says, in the middle of the Jewish temple, to a very educated, powerful audience, and all of us repent.

08:03.085 --> 08:03.666
Admit it.

08:03.906 --> 08:04.607
I have sinned.

08:04.827 --> 08:05.688
I have assaulted God.

08:05.928 --> 08:06.468
I'm guilty.

08:06.669 --> 08:07.169
I need help.

08:07.489 --> 08:17.279
We all actually are involved in the death of Jesus because we've all sinned and we need supernatural external healing just like this man needed physically.

08:18.039 --> 08:20.041
Well, okay, this God moment happens.

08:20.101 --> 08:21.422
The extraordinary happens.

08:21.482 --> 08:22.724
The guy's running around.

08:23.084 --> 08:26.087
This is Thanksgiving 101 and then the crisis comes.

08:27.128 --> 08:28.929
And why would not everyone be happy for this?

08:28.989 --> 08:33.874
I mean, why would not everyone celebrate this guy getting healed?

08:34.658 --> 08:40.986
God's extraordinary moves tend to threaten theology, tend to threaten status quo.

08:41.567 --> 08:54.303
God's new moves threaten the long, established, actually, interestingly, God's new moves sometimes threaten the places where God moved a long time ago, and that move has now turned into institutionalism and tradition.

08:55.384 --> 08:58.728
The truth repeated time and time again is when God really moves.

08:59.509 --> 09:01.211
Most people don't welcome him.

09:01.572 --> 09:03.474
Most people are not excited.

09:03.554 --> 09:06.659
Most people don't want his work, his will, his love.

09:07.701 --> 09:12.829
So Peter and John, by the way, let's just pause here, have gone up to pray.

09:13.290 --> 09:13.951
Here's the setting.

09:14.852 --> 09:25.970
So you might not know this, but every day there was at least one time when all the Jewish people in Jerusalem, especially I think the men, would go and they would pray formally at the temple.

09:26.722 --> 09:29.206
Now, we see this in Acts 2, 46.

09:29.486 --> 09:31.990
Every day they continue to meet together in the temple courts.

09:32.390 --> 09:45.310
So thousands of Jesus' followers, and almost all of them, if not all of them at this moment, are Jews, are going up for daily Jewish prayers with hundreds or thousands more who actually are not followers of Jesus.

09:45.450 --> 09:53.522
And now in this mixed crowd of those who think Jesus is the Messiah and those who don't think Jesus is the Messiah, heaven breaks out in the temple again.

09:54.018 --> 10:01.810
Peter preaches a really strong message, awe spreads, the crowd gets bigger, one or two or three hours pass, I don't know, and then we arrive at Acts 4.

10:02.551 --> 10:08.921
So the priests and the captain of the temple guard and the Sadducees came up to Peter and John while they were speaking to the people.

10:09.101 --> 10:11.084
Okay, suddenly the police show up.

10:12.747 --> 10:14.890
And they show up with a group called the Sadducees.

10:15.751 --> 10:18.776
Okay, let me unpack this for some of you who might not know about them.

10:19.457 --> 10:22.642
The Sadducees were a mix of priests and

10:22.754 --> 10:24.596
aristocracy.

10:24.716 --> 10:26.818
Basically, they had ruled for a very long time.

10:27.478 --> 10:30.261
They were a very small minority of Jews.

10:30.922 --> 10:33.024
They tended to be quite wealthy, actually.

10:33.764 --> 10:37.008
And they were not in the mainstream of Judaism at all, for a few reasons.

10:37.068 --> 10:40.151
Number one, they did not believe in a physical resurrection at all.

10:40.891 --> 10:46.116
Number two, they only believed in the Torah, Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers, Deuteronomy.

10:46.737 --> 10:49.399
They said, those are the only five books that are inspired.

10:49.920 --> 10:52.242
The rest of the Old Testament is not inspired.

10:52.642 --> 10:58.468
they said were already living in the Messianic age and only priests should deal with religious matters.

10:59.049 --> 11:00.230
Do you see the coming conflict?

11:01.051 --> 11:11.303
So the Sadducees show up in the verse 2, they are greatly disturbed because the apostles were teaching the people proclaiming in Jesus the resurrection of the dead, which they don't believe in.

11:11.323 --> 11:15.968
They seized Peter and John because it was evening, they put them in jail till the next day.

11:16.749 --> 11:21.394
Many who heard the message believe, so the number of men who believe grew to around five

11:21.890 --> 11:22.411
thousand.

11:22.651 --> 11:22.992
Okay.

11:23.593 --> 11:30.264
So early Christians, we're talking within the first two weeks, are preaching Jesus' physical resurrection from the dead?

11:30.684 --> 11:32.006
They're healing in His name.

11:32.347 --> 11:34.651
They're proclaiming Him as the only way to the Father.

11:34.951 --> 11:36.734
They're implying that He's God in flesh.

11:37.135 --> 11:44.146
They are saying He's the only one that can establish contact between God and humanity, and He's the fulfillment of the Jewish faith.

11:44.258 --> 11:53.447
And then they start seeing the healing of this man proves that Jesus has risen because by Jesus' name, Jesus is now healing through his followers.

11:53.867 --> 11:55.929
In other words, it's like positive possession.

11:56.910 --> 11:59.933
God's living in and among his people, not in the temple.

12:00.634 --> 12:08.001
So many people were coming and believing despite the leaders of the day trying to stop God's very move through his people in God's own house.

12:08.541 --> 12:10.123
You see the irony of this, right?

12:10.583 --> 12:11.104
In the temple.

12:11.784 --> 12:13.586
Now it says 5,000 men believed

12:13.762 --> 12:15.204
This doesn't include women and children.

12:15.244 --> 12:21.613
So at this moment, the Christian movement has grown to over 10,000 people like in days.

12:22.654 --> 12:24.697
Now, if you want to see a really cool connection, it's this.

12:25.218 --> 12:29.624
Jesus fed the 5,000 and now 5,000 believe.

12:29.644 --> 12:34.010
In other words, the physical food has now become the spiritual food and the movement has begun.

12:34.851 --> 12:39.518
So within two chapters, it's grown from 150 to 3000 to 10,000 or more.

12:40.319 --> 12:42.802
So Peter and John are now in jail.

12:43.298 --> 12:55.471
for healing a guy in Jesus' name, by the way, and now they have to face the same organization or legislative body that Jesus faced that actually got him killed.

12:56.452 --> 12:57.673
And it's called the Sanhedrin.

12:58.514 --> 13:00.276
Okay, some of you know about it, some of you don't.

13:00.977 --> 13:05.742
The Sanhedrin was the most important Jewish institution that existed 2,000 years ago.

13:06.363 --> 13:09.426
It was made up of the high priest and a lot of his family.

13:09.922 --> 13:11.604
the priest class and the scholars.

13:11.624 --> 13:17.210
So they are the greatest minds in Jewish law, Jewish faith, and Jewish history.

13:17.330 --> 13:25.219
And interestingly, if you read some history, the Romans had given them, say in Heteran that is, authority over every single Jew on earth.

13:25.319 --> 13:34.930
So if you were a Jew living in Alexandria and Egypt, or you were a Jew living in Rome, or you lived in Cyprus, this body had authority over you even more than the Romans did.

13:35.426 --> 13:36.847
So I've always explained it like this.

13:37.128 --> 13:48.718
For Canadians, it's like our parliament, if you're American, or from another place, it's sort of like the Congress or the Senate, and it's mixed at the same time with the Supreme Court, and it's mixed with the Vatican.

13:48.819 --> 13:52.342
So it's like the Jewish version of the Vatican, if that even makes sense with all these other things.

13:53.063 --> 13:57.987
So they spend a night in jail to basically get sobered up religiously, and it doesn't work.

13:58.768 --> 14:00.369
And then it says in verse five these words.

14:00.670 --> 14:05.234
The next day, the rulers and the elders,

14:05.698 --> 14:08.302
and the teachers of the law met in Jerusalem.

14:08.502 --> 14:13.070
Okay, this is when the show gets really wild and gets really complicated.

14:13.971 --> 14:17.356
Rulers, temple officials, Sadducees.

14:18.278 --> 14:19.119
Then you've got elders.

14:19.400 --> 14:20.041
Well, who are elders?

14:20.101 --> 14:25.910
Well, elders are like the heads of the significant families of the Jewish community.

14:26.491 --> 14:33.522
If you come from a British history, they almost feel like lords and ladies like their aristocracy, okay?

14:33.762 --> 14:36.806
And then, or landed gentry, maybe he's even a better way of saying it.

14:37.006 --> 14:46.417
And then you got the teachers of the law, different group, the theologians and the pastors who worked with the everyday people, and they're called Pharisees.

14:47.238 --> 14:50.542
And the Pharisees could not stand the Sadducees.

14:51.243 --> 14:56.850
The Pharisees accepted the whole Old Testament, Genesis to Malachi, not just the first five books,

14:57.154 --> 14:59.457
They absolutely believed in the resurrection of the dead.

14:59.837 --> 15:03.302
They were the most influential movement to the average Jewish person back then.

15:03.682 --> 15:05.665
They were all waiting for the Messiah to come.

15:05.885 --> 15:09.069
They rejected the idea that we are already living in the time of the Messiah.

15:09.850 --> 15:12.033
And so they can't stand the other side of the court.

15:12.854 --> 15:14.036
But we all know this as humans.

15:14.977 --> 15:16.759
An enemy of my enemy makes you my friend.

15:17.500 --> 15:20.003
Or a common enemy makes strange bedfellows.

15:20.644 --> 15:21.565
So that's what's happening here.

15:22.747 --> 15:24.629
And then it even gets more complicated.

15:24.769 --> 15:25.330
Verse 6.

15:25.602 --> 15:31.268
Anas the High Priest was there and so was Caiaphas and John and Alexander and others in the High Priest family.

15:31.368 --> 15:34.272
Okay, well this list really matters.

15:34.292 --> 15:42.200
Anas was the High Priest from 6 to 14 AD and then the Romans removed him from power and gave it to his family.

15:42.421 --> 15:48.667
So his son-in-law Caiaphas becomes the High Priest from 18 to 36 AD.

15:48.808 --> 15:54.674
By the way, the reason why the Pharisees couldn't stand these guys is because notice the Romans are appointing God's priests.

15:55.074 --> 16:03.042
Now, God, okay, both Anas and Caiaphas are centrally involved in the trials of Jesus and help get Jesus killed.

16:04.003 --> 16:12.352
So you've got the best lawyers and you've got the best politicians and the best theologians who, by the way, this group got Jesus killed just a few months ago.

16:13.453 --> 16:14.794
This is tense.

16:14.814 --> 16:21.161
